/**
 * @page tutorial_result_errors Tutorial: Result<T> and Error Handling
 *
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * This tutorial walks through the `Result<T, E>` pattern used throughout
 * `common_game_server` to replace exceptions with explicit, type-safe
 * error propagation. You will learn the difference between the two
 * error types (`cgs::Error` and `cgs::foundation::GameError`), how to
 * chain fallible operations without monadic combinators, how to recover
 * with fallback values, and how to surface categorized errors with
 * subsystem context for debugging.
 *
 * **Compilable version**: `examples/01_result_errors.cpp`
 * (built with `cmake --preset debug` or `cmake -DCGS_BUILD_EXAMPLES=ON`)
 *
 * @section tut_result_motivation Motivation
 *
 * Exceptions are convenient for error propagation but have three
 * properties that make them a poor fit for a 20 Hz game server:
 *
 * 1. **Invisible control flow** — you cannot tell from a function
 *    signature whether it might throw, so every call site must reason
 *    about every possible exception type that could unwind through it.
 * 2. **Unbounded cost on the unhappy path** — throwing an exception
 *    walks the stack, runs destructors, and consults RTTI. The cost is
 *    proportional to how deep the unwind goes, and in a tight game
 *    loop that can blow the 50 ms tick budget.
 * 3. **No composition** — you cannot combine two throwing functions
 *    without wrapping them in a try/catch, which means error recovery
 *    logic ends up scattered instead of concentrated at the call site.
 *
 * `common_game_server` solves all three by making errors part of the
 * type system. Every fallible function returns `Result<T, E>`. Callers
 * must explicitly check or propagate. The type-checker enforces it.
 *
 * @section tut_result_setup Setup
 *
 * Include the Result header and the game-specific error helpers:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "cgs/core/result.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/foundation/error_code.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/foundation/game_error.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/foundation/game_result.hpp"
 *
 * using cgs::foundation::ErrorCode;
 * using cgs::foundation::GameError;
 * using cgs::foundation::GameResult;
 * @endcode
 *
 * Link against `cgs::foundation_common` (`cgs_core` is pulled in
 * transitively). That's the whole setup — no extra initialization,
 * no global state, no allocator.
 *
 * @section tut_result_two_error_types The Two Error Types
 *
 * The framework has **two distinct error types** that you will see
 * throughout the codebase. Understanding the difference is the first
 * step to using `Result<T>` correctly.
 *
 * | Type | Header | Purpose |
 * |------|--------|---------|
 * | `cgs::Error` | `cgs/core/result.hpp` | Lightweight default error for library code that does not need subsystem categorization. Carries an `int code` and a `std::string message`. |
 * | `cgs::foundation::GameError` | `cgs/foundation/game_error.hpp` | Rich error for adapter and game-system methods. Carries an `ErrorCode` enum (categorized by subsystem), a message, and an `std::any` context slot for debugging payloads. |
 *
 * `Result<T>` defaults to `cgs::Error`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * template <typename T, typename E = cgs::Error>
 * class Result;
 * @endcode
 *
 * `GameResult<T>` is a type alias specialized with `GameError`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * template <typename T>
 * using GameResult = cgs::Result<T, GameError>;
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Rule of thumb**: use `GameResult<T>` everywhere you touch a
 * framework adapter (logger, database, network, monitoring, plugin
 * manager, game systems). Use the default `Result<T>` only for utility
 * code that does not have a natural subsystem.
 *
 * @section tut_result_basic Basic Result<T> API
 *
 * The `Result<T, E>` class is a tagged union of `T` and `E`. Construct
 * success and failure instances through the static factories:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto ok  = GameResult<int>::ok(42);
 * auto err = GameResult<int>::err(
 *     GameError(ErrorCode::InvalidArgument, "negative damage"));
 * @endcode
 *
 * Check which state it holds:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * if (ok.hasValue()) {
 *     int v = ok.value();   // undefined behavior if hasError()
 * }
 *
 * if (err.hasError()) {
 *     const GameError& e = err.error();
 *     // e.code(), e.message(), e.subsystem(), e.context<T>()
 * }
 *
 * // Implicit conversion to bool: true on success.
 * if (!err) {
 *     handleFailure(err.error());
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * Extract a value-or-default with `valueOr`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * std::string name =
 *     GameResult<std::string>::err(GameError(ErrorCode::NotFound, "no key"))
 *         .valueOr("anonymous");
 * // name == "anonymous"
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Never call `.value()` without first checking `.hasValue()`** — on
 * an error-bearing Result, `.value()` is undefined behavior (it
 * internally does `std::get<T>` on a variant that holds `E`).
 *
 * @section tut_result_error_codes Categorized Error Codes
 *
 * `GameError::code()` returns an `ErrorCode` enum value drawn from
 * `cgs/foundation/error_code.hpp`. The enum is organized in
 * **per-subsystem 256-value hex ranges** so you can tell which
 * subsystem produced an error just from the numeric value:
 *
 * | Range | Subsystem | Example code |
 * |-------|-----------|--------------|
 * | `0x0000–0x00FF` | General | `Success`, `InvalidArgument`, `NotFound` |
 * | `0x0100–0x01FF` | Network | `ConnectionFailed`, `Timeout`, `TlsHandshakeFailed` |
 * | `0x0200–0x02FF` | Database | `QueryFailed`, `TransactionFailed`, `ConnectionPoolExhausted` |
 * | `0x0300–0x03FF` | ECS | `EntityNotFound`, `ComponentNotFound` |
 * | `0x0400–0x04FF` | Plugin | `PluginLoadFailed`, `PluginVersionMismatch` |
 * | `0x0500–0x05FF` | Auth | `AuthenticationFailed`, `TokenExpired` |
 * | `0x0600–0x06FF` | Config | `ConfigLoadFailed`, `ConfigKeyNotFound` |
 * | `0x0700–0x07FF` | Thread | `JobScheduleFailed`, `JobTimeout` |
 * | `0x0800–0x08FF` | Logger | `LoggerNotInitialized`, `LoggerFlushFailed` |
 * | `0x0900–0x09FF` | Monitoring | `MetricNotFound` |
 * | `0x0A00–0x0AFF` | Serialization | `InvalidBinaryData`, `InvalidJsonData` |
 * | `0x0B00–0x0BFF` | GameServer | `MapInstanceNotFound`, `GameLoopNotRunning` |
 * | `0x0C00–0x0CFF` | Lobby | `QueueFull`, `PartyFull` |
 * | `0x0D00–0x0DFF` | DBProxy | `CacheMiss`, `ReplicaUnavailable` |
 * | `0x0E00–0x0EFF` | Gateway | `ConnectionLimitReached`, `RouteNotFound` |
 * | `0x0F00–0x0FFF` | Persistence | `WalWriteFailed`, `SnapshotCorrupted` |
 *
 * Use `errorSubsystem(code)` to get the subsystem name as a
 * `std::string_view` for logging:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * GameError err(ErrorCode::ConnectionFailed, "peer refused");
 * std::cout << errorSubsystem(err.code());  // "Network"
 * @endcode
 *
 * When reporting to end users, **always include both the code and the
 * subsystem** so triage tools can correlate errors across logs:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * std::cout << "error [" << errorSubsystem(err.code()) << "/"
 *           << static_cast<std::uint32_t>(err.code())
 *           << "]: " << err.message() << "\n";
 * // error [Network/256]: peer refused
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section tut_result_advanced Chaining Fallible Operations
 *
 * A real pipeline rarely has a single fallible step. The example
 * program loads a configuration in three stages:
 *
 * 1. `ReadConfig(name)` → `GameResult<std::string>`
 * 2. `ParseConfig(raw)` → `GameResult<ServerConfig>`
 * 3. `ValidateConfig(cfg)` → `GameResult<ServerConfig>`
 *
 * Each stage can fail independently, and any failure must
 * short-circuit the remainder.
 *
 * **Important**: `Result<T>` does NOT provide monadic combinators like
 * `and_then`, `map`, or `or_else`. Chaining is done with explicit early
 * returns. The pattern looks like this:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * GameResult<ServerConfig> LoadAndValidate(std::string_view name) {
 *     auto raw = ReadConfig(name);
 *     if (!raw) {
 *         return GameResult<ServerConfig>::err(raw.error());
 *     }
 *
 *     auto parsed = ParseConfig(raw.value());
 *     if (!parsed) {
 *         return GameResult<ServerConfig>::err(parsed.error());
 *     }
 *
 *     return ValidateConfig(std::move(parsed).value());
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * This is verbose but every failure point is visible in the source —
 * no hidden unwinding, no catch blocks, no resource leaks. If you find
 * the boilerplate onerous, consider wrapping it in a small helper
 * macro scoped to a single translation unit:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #define CGS_TRY(dest, expr)                                         \
 *     auto _r_##dest = (expr);                                        \
 *     if (!_r_##dest) {                                               \
 *         return GameResult<decltype(dest)>::err(_r_##dest.error());  \
 *     }                                                               \
 *     auto dest = std::move(_r_##dest).value()
 *
 * GameResult<ServerConfig> LoadAndValidate(std::string_view name) {
 *     CGS_TRY(raw, ReadConfig(name));
 *     CGS_TRY(parsed, ParseConfig(raw));
 *     return ValidateConfig(std::move(parsed));
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * **Do not put this macro in a public header.** The framework does
 * not ship such a helper by design; every adapter contract makes
 * error propagation explicit. A local helper is fine for application
 * code, but library code should spell out the early returns.
 *
 * @section tut_result_void Void Results
 *
 * Some functions do not return a value — they either succeed or fail.
 * Use `Result<void>` (or `GameResult<void>`) for these:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * GameResult<void> FlushLogs(GameLogger& logger) {
 *     return logger.flush();
 * }
 *
 * auto r = FlushLogs(logger);
 * if (!r) {
 *     std::cerr << "flush failed: " << r.error().message() << "\n";
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * The void specialization does not have a `value()` method — success
 * just means "the operation completed". Call `hasValue()` or use the
 * `bool` conversion.
 *
 * Construct success and error like this:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * GameResult<void>::ok();
 * GameResult<void>::err(GameError(ErrorCode::Timeout, "deadline exceeded"));
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section tut_result_debugging Debugging Tips
 *
 * 1. **Log subsystem + code + message together.** The subsystem tells
 *    you *where*, the code tells you *what*, and the message tells you
 *    *why*. Losing any one of the three makes triage harder.
 *
 * 2. **Attach context for complex failures.** `GameError` accepts an
 *    `std::any` context payload you can retrieve later with
 *    `error.context<MyType>()`:
 *
 *    @code{.cpp}
 *    struct QueryContext { std::string sql; int paramCount; };
 *    GameError err(ErrorCode::QueryFailed,
 *                  "syntax error near ','",
 *                  QueryContext{"SELECT * FROM ...", 3});
 *    if (auto* ctx = err.context<QueryContext>()) {
 *        std::cerr << "failed SQL: " << ctx->sql << "\n";
 *    }
 *    @endcode
 *
 * 3. **Check `hasContext()` before type-pulling.** `context<T>()`
 *    returns `nullptr` on both "no context stored" and "wrong type".
 *    Distinguish with `hasContext()` when debugging.
 *
 * 4. **Use `errorSubsystem()` in log aggregators.** If you send
 *    structured logs to Loki / ELK, add `subsystem` as an indexed
 *    field. You can then filter to a single subsystem in one query.
 *
 * 5. **Breakpoint on `.err(` in a debugger.** Because every failure
 *    goes through a named static factory, a single breakpoint on the
 *    source line can show the stack for any `GameResult` error you
 *    are investigating.
 *
 * @section tut_result_pitfalls Common Pitfalls
 *
 * 1. **Calling `.value()` on an error.** The variant holds the error,
 *    so `std::get<T>` throws `std::bad_variant_access` in debug and
 *    invokes UB in release. Always gate on `hasValue()` first.
 *
 * 2. **Copying large `T` values by accident.** `Result<T>` holds `T`
 *    by value. If `T` is a large struct, returning the Result and
 *    then calling `.value()` by const reference is free, but
 *    `auto v = result.value();` makes a copy. Use
 *    `auto&& v = std::move(result).value();` to extract by move when
 *    you own the Result.
 *
 * 3. **Mixing `cgs::Error` and `GameError`.** You cannot implicitly
 *    convert one to the other. When interfacing between library code
 *    that uses `Result<T>` and framework code that uses
 *    `GameResult<T>`, write a small adapter function that translates
 *    `cgs::Error::code` to an `ErrorCode`.
 *
 * 4. **Forgetting the `[[nodiscard]]` warning.** Most Result-returning
 *    methods are marked `[[nodiscard]]`. Ignoring one produces a
 *    compiler warning (and `-Werror` fails the build). Assign the
 *    result to a variable — don't cast to `(void)` to silence it, you
 *    are throwing away the failure signal.
 *
 * 5. **Assuming Result is thread-safe.** A `Result` object is not
 *    synchronized. If you share one across threads, provide your own
 *    mutex. In practice every Result is a local variable in the
 *    caller's frame, so this rarely matters.
 *
 * 6. **Returning `GameResult<void>::ok()` and then checking
 *    `.value()`.** The void specialization has no `value()` method —
 *    calling it is a compile error, not a runtime surprise.
 *
 * @section tut_result_performance Performance Notes
 *
 * - **`Result<T>` is stack-allocated.** It holds `T` and `E` in a
 *   `std::variant` with no heap indirection. Size is
 *   `max(sizeof(T), sizeof(E))` plus a discriminator byte.
 * - **No RTTI, no throw.** The entire Result machinery is
 *   `noexcept`-friendly (except `std::variant`'s internal
 *   `std::get_if`, which is noexcept itself).
 * - **Return-value optimization applies.** Returning a Result by
 *   value from a function is a free operation under any modern
 *   compiler — the variant is constructed directly into the
 *   caller's frame.
 * - **Movability matters for large `T`.** If `T` is expensive to
 *   copy, prefer `std::move(result).value()` over `result.value()`.
 * - **`GameError` carries `std::any`.** The context slot is empty
 *   by default (zero cost). Populating it allocates only when the
 *   payload does not fit the small-buffer optimization.
 * - **Measured cost of a successful Result return on GCC 13 + -O2**
 *   is indistinguishable from a raw `T` return. Failed Result
 *   returns cost one additional small allocation (the error message
 *   string) — comparable to a throw that unwinds zero frames, and
 *   much cheaper than a deep throw.
 *
 * @section tut_result_next Next Steps
 *
